video_title: The Shawshank Redemption - Original Theatrical Trailer
author: @aislopstop
comment_text:
Bits you may find interesting:
1. When the prison warden found the Bible where Andy had hidden the rock hammer, it was in the book of Exodus. Exodus is a Greek word meaning "departure."
2. Red describes Andy's dream as "shitty pipe dreams". During his escape to live that dream, Andy crawls through a pipe filled with raw sewage.
3. If Andy had been incarcerated in just one cell to the left he would have had nowhere to tunnel to except the next cell, and thus would have had no amazing story to tell.
4. The three times Red meets the parole board he is told "Sit", "Sit down", and lastly "Please sit down".
5. Although it is never directly stated in the film, Brooks is in prison for allegedly murdering his wife and daughter after a losing streak at poker.
6. Despite being widely considered as one of the greatest movies of all time, it didn't receive a single Oscar win, though it was nominated for seven, including Best Picture.
7. The last word spoken in the movie is "hope", a major theme of the film.

author: @traces2807
comment_text:
It took me three or four times to get through this movie all those years ago. (when renting movies was still a thing) The sheer brutality and systematic destruction of innocent human beings was really difficult to watch, but it was honestly and starkly portrayed. 
Ralph Fiennes was so brilliant in the role of monster Amon Goeth that I honestly couldn't see a film with him in it for years. A testament to his acting to say the least.
Schindler's List haunts your soul and it reaches you on another level that I can't even describe. There are moments of pure beauty too, leaving you breathless and crying.
John William's musical score is sublime and the violin solo by Itzhak Perlman gives me chills.  An absolutely stunning achievement in filmmaking.

author: @ATLcentury334
comment_text: I remember going to the Americana Theater in the Detroit area to see this when I was 15. I went with 3 cousins, I bought the program, the movie was in the large theater, and it was full. We had so much fun. The following October, 2 of my cousins dressed as Luke and Lea for Halloween. In February, my birthday came, and my dad and I always went to a movie together. I had never seen a movie twice in a theater. My mom and dad knew I‚Äôd seen it in July, and seeing a picture twice was a little unusual then, but I really wanted my dad to see it since he grew up liking Flash Gordon. It was a snowy afternoon, we got over to the theater, and I had just as fun the first time. My dad was very impressed and was surprised how much he liked it. We went to ‚ÄúLouie‚Äôs‚Äù for a late lunch. It was the last time I saw a movie with my dad, I was growing up and wanted to go with friends and dates rather than my pop. I lost him a few years ago, a few months after that, I was diagnosed with stage 3 cancer. Seeing this clip reminded me I never really had a chance to grieve my dad. I‚Äôm still recovering, but I‚Äôll always have this memory of my 16th birthday, and my dad and I enjoying one last movie before I grew up.

THAT'S movie magic.

comment_text: When I was stationed in Japan as a surface warfare officer (2017 - 2020) I met an old woman that had survived Nagasaki, she lost her parents and 7 siblings,..the love and respect she showed me even after all her family had been through will forever be engrained into my memory, I keep close a sterling silver rising sun bracelet she gifted me on my birthday, it was her oldest brother‚Äôs..she said the US Army Officers that occupied her town were very kind so maybe that had something to do with her overall outlook on life, every time I think of this movie I think of you, Mako‚Ä¶Rest In Peace.

author: @Raes96
comment_text: I don't know why people here talking about watching it once. It is very sad story, but very real. It will make you sad but also it should make you to feel very grateful and happy, even at the movie there are many happy scenes, it is showing us how we should enjoy our life in every situation. Because there is and always be only now. We live in century where we got way too much comfort, and it can cause a lot of trouble when we want to enjoy our life. We are trapped in greedy mindset of getting stimulated by internet or stuff or food or whatever, we are getting too much of everything. Seeing this makes you to rethink your life. There are important stuff, like feel the reality for a moment. Just go outside, breathe, and be happy that you live, you have food, and shelter. It is a lot to have. And i bet you got much more to be thankful for. That is what this movie is doing to me. It is making me think about what is valuable in our lives. I have seen this masterpiece hour ago for the first time, and i want to experience it again. There is no happiness without knowing or understanding what it means to be really sad. Light can exist only when you have darkness for light to uncover it.

author: @RocketRcn947
comment_text: The miniseries may have a few flaws of its own, but because the reason why this miniseries is better than the original 1980, is because it at least put in the hard work and acknowledged the source material and style of it. Whereas Kubrick just set out to make a horror film right from the beginning which didn‚Äôt work out so well for King. Stephen King‚Äôs stories may be scary, sure, but at times they also have humanity that becomes positive things at times. And it also has a lot of moments where there is family dilemma, conflict, and so much human emotion that it makes you feel sorry for the main character as he goes down his tragic story. Whereas in the film with Nicholson it could be swapped out with any other. But King‚Äôs version has an interesting three-dimensional character that‚Äôs shows step by step what he‚Äôs going through and why he‚Äôs going through it. And just because the miniseries wasn‚Äôt as scary as the film, does not mean that it isn‚Äôt good! It actually was very good and very entertaining to watch! And I saw myself watching the miseries multiple times and far more times I did than the Kubrick film where I only watched it only once or twice and that was it. King‚Äôs version made me sympathetic towards the characters which made me keep coming back even today!

comment_text:
People forget that Stephen King has gone on record stating he hates the Stanley Kubrick adaption because it diverts too far from the book he wrote and preferred the 1997 tv adaption because it‚Äôs more spot on to his work. 

Mike Flannigan also corrected Kubrick flub that in the book, the care taker who has ‚ÄúThe Shining‚Äù like Danny, didn‚Äôt die and made sure to add him back into ‚ÄúDoctor Sleep‚Äù, because he‚Äôs in the sequel book as well. 

And spoiler alert, the ending to the tv adaption is correct in how ‚ÄúThe Shining‚Äù actually ended in the book, not Kubrick‚Äôs version.

Hence why, you can hate this tv adaption all you want folks, but if Stephen King prefers it over Kubrick‚Äôs, you know you need to read the book to fully understand why!

video_title: The Shining - Official Trailer | 1997
author: @DurradonXylles
comment_text: This version of The Shining is not great, not even when it's compared to the other Stephen King adaptations that were made for television originally, but I don't think it's nearly as garbage as a lot of others here do. It's honestly mostly rather bland and forgettable, and while it does stick to the novel a lot more closely than Kubrick's version (as was mandated by King himself), it does show that a more faithful adaptation doesn't always mean a better one. That said, I will commend it on one front that it's received praise for before: the arc of Jack's possession and descent into madness. In this TV miniseries, it comes more slowly and at a more steady pace, and we see how it eats away at him throughout the progression of the story. The original film didn't quite have this, and for anyone watching the film familiar with Nicholson's works now it's kind of expected to see him flip at the end of the second act. Does this redeem the 90s miniseries? Absolutely not. It's still bland tap water viewing otherwise. That said, I will say that Jack's arc alone does make it worth a singular watch, and probably only one.

video_title: PRINCESS MONONOKE | Official English Trailer
author: @williamgregory1848
comment_text:
When people go to movies, they want to be involved in the picture so that they can get a sense of ‚ÄúI want to lose myself up on that screen for a few hours‚Äù and a sense, to know what it's like to be human. Then you come across certain kinds of films that when you go to the theater and when you see them, you're completely taken by surprise. They make you look at life a different way, and they make you look at being human a different way. They touch areas that you don't want touched sometimes. They‚Äôre provocative, which is good. And then there's that rarest of films, where when you see it continually over years (10, 15, 20, 30, 40 years) you still see more in it. And what's even better is that if you're making pictures, you go back to this well, this source for two reasons: 1.) For inspiration and 2.) To learn. To learn how to make pictures.

That‚Äôs what it felt like to me when watching Princess Mononoke. Miyazaki is such an incredible storyteller as his films often deal with humanity's relationship with nature and technology, as this film deals with themes of Shinto and environmentalism. It‚Äôs not only more beautifully drawn, it has an extremely complex and adult script and the soul of a romantic epic between Ashitaka and San, and its lush tones, breathtaking score by Joe Hisaishi and full-blooded characterizations give it the sweep of cinema's most grand canvases. It is truly a landmark in the world of animation.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi
video_title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi (1983) Trailer #1 | Movieclips Trailers
author: @KevinJohnson-hy4oc
comment_text:
This was actually the first Star Wars movie I saw, back in 1983 when it first came out in theaters.
Before I saw it, I used to play with nothing but Legos, Smurf and Muppet toys, and one day, my grandfather, who used to buy them all for me, said, "Well, kid, you're 9- years-old now, I guess you won't be playing with toys much longer."
   And then suddenly my third grade teacher took all the kids to see "Return of the Jedi" for the last day of summer school.
   3 years later, at the age of 12, I was still collecting Star Wars toys now; my bedroom was filled with them in every inch of space, and my grandfather commented at one point 
that he wanted to sue George Lucas.
   40 years later, I still have a bedroom full of Star Wars toys, and "Return of the Jedi" is still my favorite of the series (it was my grandfather's, too; to bad he couldn't have lived to see the prequels).

author: @Josefherz
comment_text:
Although it wasn't the most romantic movie I have ever watched, it was probably the most meaningful one.
Showing us the realistic side of a relationship with all its ups and downs through the years.¬†
It makes absolutely sense to be stubborn, pissed or impulsive around a person u spend your routine with.¬†
But in the end, it's this person who ll take care of u when u re sick or after u failed an exam. It's this person, whose hug and love ll mean everything to u. Despite all the fighting and disagreement. Despite how it might end, u still choose to embrace it and let every memory of it form who you are today. Because in the end it's not the destination that matters, it's the moments we spend until we get there.

author: @PetshopPlouf
comment_text: I don't usually comment on these but this movie means a lot to me because my ex and i went through a difficult breakup, we were at first colleagues who fell in love, and then we were classmates. This semester we don't have classes together because i changed my schedule, it was too hard to maintain a friendship without falling in love again. So, we have the same cinema class but separately. Our final course is to write about a movie that we chose from the teacher's list. It had about 30 movies or so.  We coincidentally both chose Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind. We would always watch movies together, and even talked about this one, it was what made us fall in love even more, and the fact that we chose the same one means a lot to me. It's an ironic conclusion.  This movie will always a special place in my heart, and him also.

author: @blanc-ugh1129
comment_text: this movie is too pure & raw. literally the epitome of a ‚Äúright person, wrong time‚Äù. this hurts because i relate to clementine and somewhat joel. i was in love with my best friend & i told him everything, to the point where i had nothing else left in my body. i trusted him and i still do, but he never trusted me. it wasn‚Äôt that i couldn‚Äôt keep anything, he never had someone to talk to other than his mother, but it was more on how i never trusted him he finally caught on and felt like a stranger, so he never ‚Äútrusted‚Äù me. it hurt knowing i was being so selfish. i love him, i never wanted to see him closed off i wanted to keep learning about him. i realized i started to treat him how i was treated in past relationships, because i was so used to the toxic environment i couldn‚Äôt fathom the idea of pure love or real love. it hurt him, because he‚Äôs liked me since middle school, but little does he know i did and still do. years later and i never thought i‚Äôd see the day where we would end up together at some point. if i knew i would‚Äôve told my middle school self to have stayed the fun loving person she was, but i let my emotions over power myself. now i just wanna forget, because these memories overpower me, but i know if i do i won‚Äôt ever progress as a human. it hurts because every minute i think about the memories i created with him & then a split second later i think about him with another person. that‚Äôs my biggest fear losing him to another, but here we are, but if somehow he sees this i just wanted to say i love you, forever.

author: @bigjanyway2224
comment_text: As a Boeing employee, words cannot express my shame for the lack of accountability for the leaders of a once proud aerospace leader. Boeing now is only a mere shadow of what was a proud, innovative fantastic company.  The Chicago leadership only have concerns about stock dividends and their  bonus percentage. The IAM, SPEEA,salary folks still take the greatest of pride about building the best, safest aircraft in the world. Unfortunately leadership talk the talk but never walk the walk. 25 million dollars severance to the disgraced CEO. The man who was personally responsible for the tragic deaths of 300+ souls. To the families of those who lives will forever be touch by these events, we those build the planes want you to know that ever bolt,  rivet and flight system we put in is done with your sacrifice in the front of minds. You will NEVER be forgotten by us. To us safety is all that matters. May you one day find peace.

Looks fabulous, but I do hope it leads to a bridge "somehow" from this horrific tragedy.  The Catholic church burned people at the stake and abused others, so we -for good cause-don't wish to stoop to overly aggressive measures.  It is a delicate time in this country of such divisions. 

Personally, I continue to ask the Pontiff for letting "Mary" out of the closet.  Scriptures are quite obvious as to having other children and we do need a good Mother role model as well as a good FAMILY role model.  

Hence, priests also should be offered the opportunity to marry.  How can one tout family values with no equal status to a Mother figure and have family models within the spirituals of the Bible as well as in the church at present?  

Best to you! (By the way, being from WI, I don't like Cardinal Dolan from Milwaukee as having gotten an advancement from Bishop to Cardinal considering the attempt to move funds from compensating victims in Milwaukee while he was Bishop there.)

author: @rohanmarkjay
comment_text: Col. Saito portrayed in the movie is actually one of the more human Japanese prison commanders in WW2. In reality the average Japanese Prison Commander in the Jungle in WW2 was far worse. I guess Col. Nicholson character really well played by Alec Guinness was lucky to have reasonable minded Japanese military commander of the camp. Col. Nicholson was aware of it. Thats why he decided to do business with Col. Saito. For a period actually respected and liked each other. Really good film beatifully shot. First saw it as a kid in the 1980s and was a big fan of the movie ever since gives a good account what allied soldiers British, Americans, Canadians, Australians, New Zealanders went through fighting the Japanese in Asia and the Pacific in WW2.

author: @itsgettingstrangeroutthere
comment_text:
Lets get real, because of the iconic nature of the original ANYTHING that comes out to try and surpass, link, sequel, prequel, whatever... it just won't touch it. It's not going to be the same and firstly that's because of the time the original came out. Secondly, it's a different world, a much more opinionated and critical world we live in. You have to look beyond the original to enjoy this one for what it is. Expectations are far higher nowadays and people are always chasing perfection. Thankfully it's not a remake. If the original had never existed and this movie was the first of its kind then it would be likely be praised to high heaven. 

Just enjoy it for what it is.

author: @Totoro_Bhai
comment_text: I know I'm pretty late, but I watched it yesterday. I was mesmerized by how brilliant this movie is. The storytelling was on another level. The set design, costume design, and writing were fabulous. I also loved the acting performances, my favorites being Kim Min-hee (as Hideko) and Ha Jung-woo (as Count Fujiwara). Korean Cinema never fails to amaze me. I really want to suggest this movie to my friends but most of them are not comfortable reading subtitles while watching and the $ex scenes might be too much for them.

author: @FigmentJedi
comment_text:
Oz is a real place in the books and six books in, Dorothy moves there with her aunt and uncle permanently when the farm goes belly up. The "All just a dream ending" was something the studio executives tacked on because they thought 1930s audiences wouldn't accept the idea of a girl going to an actual fairy tale kingdom. 
Also Glinda and the Witch of the North were two separate characters that they just merged for the movie because they didn't want to film the second quest to find Glinda that involved a china doll kingdom and the Cowardly Lion killing a giant spider to truly earn the title of King of the Forest.

author: @TheWat870
comment_text: As much as i love Tokyo Story (it's one of my all time favourite films), this trailer really misrepresents its subtlety and nuance.  It isn't a film that sweeps you away with acts of melodrama and a sweeping orchestral soundtrack.  Its unmatched power comes from the intense emotions that exist beneath the parents' stoic demeanours but which they cannot allow themselves to express; the soft melancholy behind their ever-genial countenances.  Never has such a gentle film packed such a gut punch.

author: @traces2807
comment_text:
It took me three or four times to get through this movie all those years ago. (when renting movies was still a thing) The sheer brutality and systematic destruction of innocent human beings was really difficult to watch, but it was honestly and starkly portrayed. 
Ralph Fiennes was so brilliant in the role of monster Amon Goeth that I honestly couldn't see a film with him in it for years. A testament to his acting to say the least.
Schindler's List haunts your soul and it reaches you on another level that I can't even describe. There are moments of pure beauty too, leaving you breathless and crying.
John William's musical score is sublime and the violin solo by Itzhak Perlman gives me chills.  An absolutely stunning achievement in filmmaking.

video_title: Forrest Gump (1994) Trailer #1 | Movieclips Classic Trailers
author: @aislopstop
comment_text:
Kindly pause scrolling and make space for the following information in your memory banks:
1. Tom Hanks was not paid for this film. Instead, he took percentage points which ultimately netted him in the region of $40 million.
2. With every transition of Forrest's age, one thing remains the same. In the first scene of each transition, he wears a blue plaid shirt.
3. Forrest's college football uniform is always spotless, due to the fact that no-one is fast enough to catch him.
4. During the ping-pong matches, there was no ball; it was entirely CGI, animated to meet the actors' paddles.
5. Chris Rock, Eddie Murphy, and Martin Lawrence were considered for the role of Bubba.
6. Jodie Foster, Nicole Kidman, and Demi Moore turned down the role of Jenny Curran.
7. Haley Joel Osment was cast in the film after the casting director had noticed him in a Pizza Hut commercial.
8. Forrest and Dan's Shrimp Emporium, "Bubba Gump," is now a themed restaurant in 33 locations around the world.
9. After his experience playing lieutenant Dan, Gary Sinise established a charity to help disabled veterans. To date he's raised over $280 million.
10. Selected by the Library of Congress for preservation in the National Film Registry in December 2011 as being "culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant."

author: @helermshake4649
comment_text:
Saddest part is the true story is base on George Stinney Jr. was the youngest person sentenced to death in the 20th century in the United States.

He was only 14 when he was executed by electric chair.

During his trial, until the day of his execution, he always carried a bible in his hands, claiming for innocence.
He was accused of killing two white girls, Betty of 11 years old and Mary of 7, the bodies were found near the house where the teenager resided with his parents.

At that time all the jurors were white. The trial lasted only 2 hours and the sentence was handed down 10 minutes later.
The child's parents were threatened and prevented from giving him gifts in the courtroom and then expelling them from that city.

Before the execution, George spent 81 days without being able to see his parents.
He was trapped in a solitary cell, 80 km from his city. He was heard alone without the presence of his parents or a lawyer.

He was electrocuted with 5,380 volts in the head.

70 years later, his innocence was finally proven by a judge in South Carolina. The beam with which the two girls were killed, weighed more than 19.07 kilograms. Therefore, it was impossible for Stinney to be able to lift it, let alone be able to hit hard enough to kill the two girls. The child was innocent, someone put everything together to blame him just for being black.

Stephen King was inspired by this case to write his book The Green Mile, which was taken to theaters in 1999.

author: @Raes96
comment_text: I don't know why people here talking about watching it once. It is very sad story, but very real. It will make you sad but also it should make you to feel very grateful and happy, even at the movie there are many happy scenes, it is showing us how we should enjoy our life in every situation. Because there is and always be only now. We live in century where we got way too much comfort, and it can cause a lot of trouble when we want to enjoy our life. We are trapped in greedy mindset of getting stimulated by internet or stuff or food or whatever, we are getting too much of everything. Seeing this makes you to rethink your life. There are important stuff, like feel the reality for a moment. Just go outside, breathe, and be happy that you live, you have food, and shelter. It is a lot to have. And i bet you got much more to be thankful for. That is what this movie is doing to me. It is making me think about what is valuable in our lives. I have seen this masterpiece hour ago for the first time, and i want to experience it again. There is no happiness without knowing or understanding what it means to be really sad. Light can exist only when you have darkness for light to uncover it.

author: @lilPopper
comment_text: I watched both films -- The Departed and Infernal Affairs with an open mind. Both were good in their own rights -- not to mention the differences were necessary for cultural preferences to meet the different demographic audiences. Personally I like Infernal Affairs better because I felt more connected with the characters. Also, Infernal Affairs is a trilogy (part 2 is a prequel to the first film, and part 3 was jumping between time lines) to help more with the character development -- for me that was easier to retain information better than cramming so much into one film like what The Departed did.

What I love about Harmonica‚Äôs character is that you can tell his silent, stoic persona is just a mask yet he never takes off that mask. 

He remains composed, calm and calculating every millisecond he is onscreen, yet his eyes reveal the visceral emotion of someone who wants to let everything out. It makes you want to know more about him, what he has experienced and how he has trained himself to get to this point of his life.

Everyone remembers Eastwood‚Äôs The Man With No Name, but Harmonica is honestly a much better character because of his depth and Bronson‚Äôs extraordinarily subtle performance as him.

comment_text: Something very special about this movie. I don't know exactly what it is. The fun and excitement. The beautiful unique locations. Ford was born for this role. It's such a special movie. It just can't be recreated. I think when a director truly loves their project and it's their story. Their vision being filmed. It somehow blends into the film and turns a movie into a masterpiece. author: @Amber_xo_133
comment_text: Because Danny Lloyd was so young, and since it was his first acting job, Stanley Kubrick was highly protective of the child. During the shooting of the movie, Lloyd was under the impression that the film he was making was a drama, not a horror movie. In fact, when Wendy carries Danny away while shouting at Jack in the Colorado Lounge, she is actually carrying a life-size dummy, so Lloyd would not have to be in the scene. He only realized the truth several years later, when he was shown a heavily edited version of the film. He did not see the uncut version of the film until he was seventeen, eleven years after he had made it.

video_title: The Great Dictator (1940) Review
author: @TheClagga
comment_text: This is a war comedy with quirkiness! You‚Äôve got mixtures of black comedy, emotion, humanity and power throughout from what is this masterful piece of film work from Chaplin! It‚Äôs so clever to see how this legendary filmmaker can portray these two characters who are both on different sides as well as showing how they can be portrayed effectively! The performance for the Hitler esque character of Hynkel really blew me away with the use of the dramatic presences and even in the German speech earlier on as an example in this film and that‚Äôs when you know that Chaplin can show the ability to create anything that can work on set with whatever he chooses to do for the films that he can make! It‚Äôs so satisfying to see some resemblance brought in from the Tramp into this other character known as The Barber and can still show the classic clumsiness and slapstick comedy just like from the previous films! The fighting scene with the food when both Hynkel and Napoloni react from the mustard is hilariously funny too! The beginning with the sequence from WW1 is exceptionally well framed with the cinematography and I also really enjoyed the comedic acts with the bombs and planes etc! Also we certainly cannot mention this film without the speech at the very end and that has to be the perfect moment to send this film off on a high note! This speech is and will be for a long time, my absolute favourite piece of film monologue ever!! It‚Äôs such a moving, thrilling and inspiring scene and to see Chaplin with how he expresses these words shows how passionate he is to deliver such lines with courage and dignity! This incredible monologue in many ways is still relatable and even to this day!! The last few shots from the ending with Hannah looking up was so touching and what a way to end this masterpiece! Tommy! I think you‚Äôll be pleased to hear that this film is now to be one of my absolute favourite comedies and into my Top 3 in that category as well as this to be my 2nd favourite Chaplin film! Not only that but this film is to also go somewhere into my Top 20! üòäüé•üé¨

comment_text: This is an excellent film: a beautifully made crime mystery thriller.  In Mifune and Nakada, Kurosawa had what Hitchcok usually lacked, two absolutely first class actors. I mean actors, not personalities like JImmy Stewart, who did not act. And this film is stunningly directed all the way through.  The scene at the end, where Mifune meets the killer is perfection.  And his performance is also first rate.  You really feel the waste of a brilliant human being.  A flawless genre piece.

author: @iamshadowbanned699
comment_text: One night when I was younger and couldn't sleep, I went to the living room and my mother was watching this movie. I decided to sit down and watch, and I thought I was in for a snoozefest. Boy, was I wrong. It's one of my most favorite films of all-time.

author: @sarcasticsugar4466
comment_text: One of the greatest movies I have ever seen in my life. EVER. It won 8 oscars all of which it deserved - but it deserved one more, an oscar for Tom Hulce who acted as Mozart!

video_title: Amadeus (1984) Official Trailer - F. Murray Abraham, Mozart Drama Movie HD
author: @nicholasjoost5111
comment_text: I don't think I've ever obsessed over a film like I have with Amadeus. I can't stop digging into this movie. Layer after layer: The battle we face when place our own will against the will of the father. The fact that even a good man -- any one of us -- will commit evil and be consumed by it, as long as he feels justified. The question of talent -- where does it come from, and how can all men be equal when some men are so clearly naturally better than us? That's just scratching the surface!! Love Amadeus!!

video_title: Amadeus (1984) Official Trailer - F. Murray Abraham, Mozart Drama Movie HD
author: @mikeklimczak9600
comment_text: This film changed my life. I watched it for the first time in college during a music appreciation class that I wasn't really interested in taking to begin with. I've since learned to read, write, and compose music, attend symphonies, operas, ballets, and even studied violin for some time. What a timeless film that will continue to transcend time.

author: @manneianevski
comment_text:
First time I saw this movie, it was in 2004, I was 21. I told myself to never do drugs after watching it, and didn't watch it since.
Rewatch it tonight in 2023. I felt into cathinones injection addiction 2 years ago.
I decided myself to quit a year ago, but still had relapse. Lost everything : friends, family, job. But I went back on track and found a new job, and kept injecting those craps...
Last week-end, I had an overdose for the first time. This time, I stop for good. Even if it is going to be painful, hard, even if the withdrawal symptoms will be horrible, even if my mood swings in the hardest day.
I needed to rewatch this movie. I am still lucky to be in good health condition, I refuse to end up like any of the characters of this movie.
And I'm grateful that this movie exists, it is the kind of shock that you need to remind you to stay away from those craps.
For those dealing with addiction : you're gonna make it. You're strong, you worth it, and there is more people than you think who cares about you. Be brave ‚ù§ It will be hard in the beginning, but it will worth it on the long term.

author: @williamjones6031
comment_text:
1. Best guess is that Han was Jabba's "trophy" for about a year and a half before the rescue.
2. Vader discovered Leia as Luke's sister because he could feel it through Luke.
Luke didn't know that until just before then.
3. Luke's light saber is green because he lost his old one along with his hand so they decided to make it green because it worked better in the desert background landscape.
4. Everybody is freaking out because Luke and Leia kissed mostly because she was trying to piss off Han. They didn't know they are related.
5. The "I love you. I know" was written into the script to get Leia the shot to say it to Han.
6. This was Warrick Davis'/Lead Ewok first acting gig. He was only 13. 
"Willow" is his lead with Val Kilmer and worth a first time/share.
7. Awesome camera work with the race through the forest. Nobody in their right mind would go that fast.
8. Carrie Fisher said in her biography that the most satisfying part in her Star Wars experience was choking out Jabba.  
9. Jedi is plural. With Luke and Leia leading the way they can reestablish the Jedi back into the galaxy. 
10.  Ford wanted Han to die in the last episode.
11. IMVHO this is the best of the original 6 George Lucas Star Wars. After the first six he sold it to Disney, and everything changed. Sadly

90 YEARS OF METROPOLIS
Come to celebrate the 90 YEARS OF METROPOLIS in Berlin where the film was created and had its world premier on January 10, 2017 at Babylon Kino, accompanied with a live Orchestra. Two more performances on January 11th and 12th.
Info & tickets: https://www.startnext.com/metropolis90babylon/rewards

author: @ShiftedObjectDeposit
comment_text:
In a futuristic city sharply divided between the working class and the city planners, the son of the city's mastermind falls in love with a working class prophet who predicts the coming of a savior to mediate their differences.

153 min - Drama | Sci-Fi, Director: Fritz Lang
Release dates: 10 January 1927 (premiere), 13 March 1927 (USA)

Official site: http://www.kinolorber.com/metropolis/

IMDB 8.4/10 http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017136/
Critic reviews: (221) http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0017136/externalreviews

"There are certain films come with a weight of expectation as there has been so much written and said about them that you watch them expecting a masterpiece; these would include movies like Citizen Kane, Tokyo Story and Metropolis. Regarded as the granddaddy of science fiction films which has influenced everything from Blade Runner to Dark City and The Matrix and even entering the world of music videos such as Radio Gaga by Queen and Madonna's Express Yourself, Metropolis is a giant movie that has flummoxed film historians since its release in January of 1927."

movie_title: indiana jones and the last crusade
video_title: Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade (1989) - Teaser Trailer [HD]
author: @o.portista
comment_text: Like all Indiana Jones Movie, this was perfection. With Indiana Jones and the Raiders of the Lost Ark, being the best, this can be easily said as the second best, and close to its first. With Legendary Casts, Soundtracks, and storyline made the movie what its worth. Harrison Ford & Sean Connery, was such an iconic duo on this film. Compared to the last, and it's critics, this one was a clear redemption, and one where we got so much more than we deserved. We got to see the many perspectives of Indiana Jones, some old classic characters returning, and a movie that was extra long for us, with an action pact timeline. Honestly sad that they don't make movies like these anymore, and that many of the cast are gone now, and may the legend Sean Connery rest in peace. In all Honesty here, if your looking for an action pact, comedic, and with adventure movie, this is it. What a blast it was to re-watch it during Christmas!!!!!!!!!

video_title: Inside Out - Official US Trailer
author: @PixarShark
comment_text:
Two things I noticed:

1. From what we can see of the mom's "memories" (those colored orbs in the background), she seems to have a pretty calm demeanor. I don't see a single red orb back there.
2. This is actually quite perfect because the emotions in the parents' minds are a well-oiled machine. They're generally on the same level with each other and everything's in control. In Riley's growing mind, however, her emotions seem to be having a hard time getting along and maintaining peace and understanding each other.

Pixar, this is why I love you again and again. :D

video_title: Logan Official Trailer #1 (2017) Hugh Jackman Wolverine Movie HD
author: @kamikoblalark3896
comment_text:
This movie is going to be ridiculously sad - it marks the beginning of the end of an era. Hugh and Patrick were the first big characters in our Marvel Cinematic Universe (yes, I'm including Fox into that), and to see them go, 17 years later, in such an emotional and intimate way is a reminder that time ensures nothing lasts forever. It may just be a movie franchise, but for many people, it is part of our childhood, or at the very least, something we turned to for entertainment for years (especially if you were a big comic nerd like me). These movies were my childhood, and I guess it sort of signifies that it's time to move on.

These movies won't be the same without Hugh and Patrick.

Now to start bracing myself for the same to happen with the Marvel property - Iron Man, Thor, Captain America, etc... after these Avengers movies, who knows how long it'll be before they pass the baton?

author: @kemycake
comment_text: I had watched this when it was released through my uncle, who was (and is, if I based off of my observations) a very articulate and sentimental man. He was brave and creative. He loved weird movies with deeper meanings that as I a nine-year old child, I could never comprehend. But as I grew older, I realized it was related to what life is really about. Mary and Max was inexplicably odd back then, but sailing through the sea of life with a boat of loneliness like the both of them...it is more meaningful to me now. I was open for ideas and heroines with greater abilities than their own size, and believing that I can create an impact if not on everyone, but on at least one person. But my uncle doesn't talk to me anymore because of some family issues, but this movie reminded me of how he played the greatest role of shaping my creativity and outlook about life.

comment_text:
This movie is hauntingly beautiful. Cannot believe that it has been 15 years since this movie came out and now 15 years later Adam Elliott has another fantastic movie out: Memoir Of A Snail (which similarly to Mary and Max begins in the 1970‚Äôs (specifically 1972) and spans decades into the protagonist‚Äôs life up until the 90‚Äôs/2000‚Äôs). 

Saw this movie as a teenager by accident, as I didn‚Äôt see it when it first came out because I was too young (I was 10 when this movie came out). 

The best way I would describe it to someone is a platonic ‚ÄúHarold and Maude‚Äù meets a platonic ‚ÄúYou‚Äôve Got Mail‚Äù, if it were directed by Tim Burton, with a touch of Richard Linklater‚Äôs ‚ÄúBefore‚Äù trilogy or ‚ÄúBoyhood‚Äù. 

Have to say, rewatching this now, the ending hits harder now that we have lost both Barry Humphries AND Phillip Seymour Hoffmann.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)
author: @mvies77
comment_text: I saw this on TV at age 10 and I was inthralled. The light through the trees. The clouds. The various interpretations. The drama. I knew I was watching something unique and brilliant and I never forgot it. It is a haunting movie that lingers in your imagination. He was a genius.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)
author: @tasgeo
comment_text: One of the two or three most important movies ever made. The story of human communication in a world where people live next to each other yet in completely different universes. The cynic, the idealist and the simple everyday fallible person. Who holds the hope of mankinds future ? Magnificent as a concept, frightening as a story, technically superb and philosophically unsurpassed. I don't think there are enough stars to rate this movie.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)

comment_text: i love how most people are sharing that they got to know about this film in variety of degree courses- filmmaking, criminology, etc. for me it was referred by my prof. in an english literature lecture explaining the concept of 'ideation'. it requires the reader to put different perspectives together in order to understand the text as a whole.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)
author: @youtubister
comment_text:
One of the most influential films ever made: stunning in concept and breath taking in execution. As flawless a film as you will find.

This film opened the door for me to the work of Akira Kurosawa. I vividly remember seeing it in the cinema in the late 60's.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)
author: @Atombender
comment_text: One of the great movies that keeps you busy long after the final scene. Which story is true? Which story has a degree of truth in it? Is everyone lying to put themselves in a better light? It's completely up to the viewer what to believe and there's no definite answer.

video_title: Rashomon Trailer (Akira Kurosawa, 1950)

video_title: The Shawshank Redemption - Original Theatrical Trailer
author: @aislopstop
comment_text:
Bits you may find interesting:
1. When the prison warden found the Bible where Andy had hidden the rock hammer, it was in the book of Exodus. Exodus is a Greek word meaning "departure."
2. Red describes Andy's dream as "shitty pipe dreams". During his escape to live that dream, Andy crawls through a pipe filled with raw sewage.
3. If Andy had been incarcerated in just one cell to the left he would have had nowhere to tunnel to except the next cell, and thus would have had no amazing story to tell.
4. The three times Red meets the parole board he is told "Sit", "Sit down", and lastly "Please sit down".
5. Although it is never directly stated in the film, Brooks is in prison for allegedly murdering his wife and daughter after a losing streak at poker.
6. Despite being widely considered as one of the greatest movies of all time, it didn't receive a single Oscar win, though it was nominated for seven, including Best Picture.
7. The last word spoken in the movie is "hope", a major theme of the film.

author: @traces2807
comment_text:
It took me three or four times to get through this movie all those years ago. (when renting movies was still a thing) The sheer brutality and systematic destruction of innocent human beings was really difficult to watch, but it was honestly and starkly portrayed. 
Ralph Fiennes was so brilliant in the role of monster Amon Goeth that I honestly couldn't see a film with him in it for years. A testament to his acting to say the least.
Schindler's List haunts your soul and it reaches you on another level that I can't even describe. There are moments of pure beauty too, leaving you breathless and crying.
John William's musical score is sublime and the violin solo by Itzhak Perlman gives me chills.  An absolutely stunning achievement in filmmaking.

author: @ATLcentury334
comment_text: I remember going to the Americana Theater in the Detroit area to see this when I was 15. I went with 3 cousins, I bought the program, the movie was in the large theater, and it was full. We had so much fun. The following October, 2 of my cousins dressed as Luke and Lea for Halloween. In February, my birthday came, and my dad and I always went to a movie together. I had never seen a movie twice in a theater. My mom and dad knew I‚Äôd seen it in July, and seeing a picture twice was a little unusual then, but I really wanted my dad to see it since he grew up liking Flash Gordon. It was a snowy afternoon, we got over to the theater, and I had just as fun the first time. My dad was very impressed and was surprised how much he liked it. We went to ‚ÄúLouie‚Äôs‚Äù for a late lunch. It was the last time I saw a movie with my dad, I was growing up and wanted to go with friends and dates rather than my pop. I lost him a few years ago, a few months after that, I was diagnosed with stage 3 cancer. Seeing this clip reminded me I never really had a chance to grieve my dad. I‚Äôm still recovering, but I‚Äôll always have this memory of my 16th birthday, and my dad and I enjoying one last movie before I grew up.

author: @jkdbuck7670
comment_text:
A few years ago, we told our then 12 year old son we were going to watch Back To The Future.  It was met with doubt and "I don't want watch YOUR OLD crappy movies." We told him he was gonna sit and watch it, end of discussion.

He LOVED IT! As soon at the DeLorean flew off and vanished, he asked if there was another one!    We put on 2 and then right after that we put on 3.   He went from being a doubter at the beginning of the first one to jumping up and down on the couch during the train sequence in Part 3 when they're trying to get that locomotive up to 88 mph.

THAT'S movie magic.

comment_text: When I was stationed in Japan as a surface warfare officer (2017 - 2020) I met an old woman that had survived Nagasaki, she lost her parents and 7 siblings,..the love and respect she showed me even after all her family had been through will forever be engrained into my memory, I keep close a sterling silver rising sun bracelet she gifted me on my birthday, it was her oldest brother‚Äôs..she said the US Army Officers that occupied her town were very kind so maybe that had something to do with her overall outlook on life, every time I think of this movie I think of you, Mako‚Ä¶Rest In Peace.

video_title: Grave of the Fireflies | Official Trailer | Netflix
author: @Raes96
comment_text: I don't know why people here talking about watching it once. It is very sad story, but very real. It will make you sad but also it should make you to feel very grateful and happy, even at the movie there are many happy scenes, it is showing us how we should enjoy our life in every situation. Because there is and always be only now. We live in century where we got way too much comfort, and it can cause a lot of trouble when we want to enjoy our life. We are trapped in greedy mindset of getting stimulated by internet or stuff or food or whatever, we are getting too much of everything. Seeing this makes you to rethink your life. There are important stuff, like feel the reality for a moment. Just go outside, breathe, and be happy that you live, you have food, and shelter. It is a lot to have. And i bet you got much more to be thankful for. That is what this movie is doing to me. It is making me think about what is valuable in our lives. I have seen this masterpiece hour ago for the first time, and i want to experience it again. There is no happiness without knowing or understanding what it means to be really sad. Light can exist only when you have darkness for light to uncover it.

video_title: The Shining - Official Trailer | 1997
author: @RocketRcn947
comment_text: The miniseries may have a few flaws of its own, but because the reason why this miniseries is better than the original 1980, is because it at least put in the hard work and acknowledged the source material and style of it. Whereas Kubrick just set out to make a horror film right from the beginning which didn‚Äôt work out so well for King. Stephen King‚Äôs stories may be scary, sure, but at times they also have humanity that becomes positive things at times. And it also has a lot of moments where there is family dilemma, conflict, and so much human emotion that it makes you feel sorry for the main character as he goes down his tragic story. Whereas in the film with Nicholson it could be swapped out with any other. But King‚Äôs version has an interesting three-dimensional character that‚Äôs shows step by step what he‚Äôs going through and why he‚Äôs going through it. And just because the miniseries wasn‚Äôt as scary as the film, does not mean that it isn‚Äôt good! It actually was very good and very entertaining to watch! And I saw myself watching the miseries multiple times and far more times I did than the Kubrick film where I only watched it only once or twice and that was it. King‚Äôs version made me sympathetic towards the characters which made me keep coming back even today!

author: @rhimaginemua
comment_text:
People forget that Stephen King has gone on record stating he hates the Stanley Kubrick adaption because it diverts too far from the book he wrote and preferred the 1997 tv adaption because it‚Äôs more spot on to his work. 

Mike Flannigan also corrected Kubrick flub that in the book, the care taker who has ‚ÄúThe Shining‚Äù like Danny, didn‚Äôt die and made sure to add him back into ‚ÄúDoctor Sleep‚Äù, because he‚Äôs in the sequel book as well. 

And spoiler alert, the ending to the tv adaption is correct in how ‚ÄúThe Shining‚Äù actually ended in the book, not Kubrick‚Äôs version.

Hence why, you can hate this tv adaption all you want folks, but if Stephen King prefers it over Kubrick‚Äôs, you know you need to read the book to fully understand why!

video_title: The Shining - Official Trailer | 1997
author: @DurradonXylles
comment_text: This version of The Shining is not great, not even when it's compared to the other Stephen King adaptations that were made for television originally, but I don't think it's nearly as garbage as a lot of others here do. It's honestly mostly rather bland and forgettable, and while it does stick to the novel a lot more closely than Kubrick's version (as was mandated by King himself), it does show that a more faithful adaptation doesn't always mean a better one. That said, I will commend it on one front that it's received praise for before: the arc of Jack's possession and descent into madness. In this TV miniseries, it comes more slowly and at a more steady pace, and we see how it eats away at him throughout the progression of the story. The original film didn't quite have this, and for anyone watching the film familiar with Nicholson's works now it's kind of expected to see him flip at the end of the second act. Does this redeem the 90s miniseries? Absolutely not. It's still bland tap water viewing otherwise. That said, I will say that Jack's arc alone does make it worth a singular watch, and probably only one.

author: @nicholasjoost5111
comment_text: I don't think I've ever obsessed over a film like I have with Amadeus. I can't stop digging into this movie. Layer after layer: The battle we face when place our own will against the will of the father. The fact that even a good man -- any one of us -- will commit evil and be consumed by it, as long as he feels justified. The question of talent -- where does it come from, and how can all men be equal when some men are so clearly naturally better than us? That's just scratching the surface!! Love Amadeus!!

video_title: PRINCESS MONONOKE | Official English Trailer
author: @williamgregory1848
comment_text:
When people go to movies, they want to be involved in the picture so that they can get a sense of ‚ÄúI want to lose myself up on that screen for a few hours‚Äù and a sense, to know what it's like to be human. Then you come across certain kinds of films that when you go to the theater and when you see them, you're completely taken by surprise. They make you look at life a different way, and they make you look at being human a different way. They touch areas that you don't want touched sometimes. They‚Äôre provocative, which is good. And then there's that rarest of films, where when you see it continually over years (10, 15, 20, 30, 40 years) you still see more in it. And what's even better is that if you're making pictures, you go back to this well, this source for two reasons: 1.) For inspiration and 2.) To learn. To learn how to make pictures.

That‚Äôs what it felt like to me when watching Princess Mononoke. Miyazaki is such an incredible storyteller as his films often deal with humanity's relationship with nature and technology, as this film deals with themes of Shinto and environmentalism. It‚Äôs not only more beautifully drawn, it has an extremely complex and adult script and the soul of a romantic epic between Ashitaka and San, and its lush tones, breathtaking score by Joe Hisaishi and full-blooded characterizations give it the sweep of cinema's most grand canvases. It is truly a landmark in the world of animation.

movie_title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi
video_title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi (1983) Trailer #1 | Movieclips Trailers
author: @KevinJohnson-hy4oc
comment_text:
This was actually the first Star Wars movie I saw, back in 1983 when it first came out in theaters.
Before I saw it, I used to play with nothing but Legos, Smurf and Muppet toys, and one day, my grandfather, who used to buy them all for me, said, "Well, kid, you're 9- years-old now, I guess you won't be playing with toys much longer."
   And then suddenly my third grade teacher took all the kids to see "Return of the Jedi" for the last day of summer school.
   3 years later, at the age of 12, I was still collecting Star Wars toys now; my bedroom was filled with them in every inch of space, and my grandfather commented at one point 
that he wanted to sue George Lucas.
   40 years later, I still have a bedroom full of Star Wars toys, and "Return of the Jedi" is still my favorite of the series (it was my grandfather's, too; to bad he couldn't have lived to see the prequels).

video_title: Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind Trailer
author: @Josefherz
comment_text:
Although it wasn't the most romantic movie I have ever watched, it was probably the most meaningful one.
Showing us the realistic side of a relationship with all its ups and downs through the years.¬†
It makes absolutely sense to be stubborn, pissed or impulsive around a person u spend your routine with.¬†
But in the end, it's this person who ll take care of u when u re sick or after u failed an exam. It's this person, whose hug and love ll mean everything to u. Despite all the fighting and disagreement. Despite how it might end, u still choose to embrace it and let every memory of it form who you are today. Because in the end it's not the destination that matters, it's the moments we spend until we get there.

author: @PetshopPlouf
comment_text: I don't usually comment on these but this movie means a lot to me because my ex and i went through a difficult breakup, we were at first colleagues who fell in love, and then we were classmates. This semester we don't have classes together because i changed my schedule, it was too hard to maintain a friendship without falling in love again. So, we have the same cinema class but separately. Our final course is to write about a movie that we chose from the teacher's list. It had about 30 movies or so.  We coincidentally both chose Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind. We would always watch movies together, and even talked about this one, it was what made us fall in love even more, and the fact that we chose the same one means a lot to me. It's an ironic conclusion.  This movie will always a special place in my heart, and him also.

author: @blanc-ugh1129
comment_text: this movie is too pure & raw. literally the epitome of a ‚Äúright person, wrong time‚Äù. this hurts because i relate to clementine and somewhat joel. i was in love with my best friend & i told him everything, to the point where i had nothing else left in my body. i trusted him and i still do, but he never trusted me. it wasn‚Äôt that i couldn‚Äôt keep anything, he never had someone to talk to other than his mother, but it was more on how i never trusted him he finally caught on and felt like a stranger, so he never ‚Äútrusted‚Äù me. it hurt knowing i was being so selfish. i love him, i never wanted to see him closed off i wanted to keep learning about him. i realized i started to treat him how i was treated in past relationships, because i was so used to the toxic environment i couldn‚Äôt fathom the idea of pure love or real love. it hurt him, because he‚Äôs liked me since middle school, but little does he know i did and still do. years later and i never thought i‚Äôd see the day where we would end up together at some point. if i knew i would‚Äôve told my middle school self to have stayed the fun loving person she was, but i let my emotions over power myself. now i just wanna forget, because these memories overpower me, but i know if i do i won‚Äôt ever progress as a human. it hurts because every minute i think about the memories i created with him & then a split second later i think about him with another person. that‚Äôs my biggest fear losing him to another, but here we are, but if somehow he sees this i just wanted to say i love you, forever.

comment_text: I've been interested in Billy the Kid for almost 20 years and when I first heard about this movie, I was skeptical but the trailer has gotten my hopes up that it might be ok.  I'm skeptical of this actor's portrayal of Billy but I'll wait until I've seen the movie to make a judgement.  I'm happy to see that the movie includes some real historical events, like the shootout at Stinking Springs, Garrett bringing Billy into town in a wagon and standing off the locals who want him, the fight with Bell on the staircase and Billy on the balcony of the courthouse, just before he makes his last get-away.

comment_text: In 1961 it was only sixteen years since Japan had been defeated in the second world war. The Japanese were enduring defeat, rebuilding their land, their country, and trying to rebuild the Japanese national spirit. This movie was a reminder to a new generation of Japanese youth - This is what you are - this is your heritage - this is what your ancestors, who now watch over you, once were. Grow to be men and women. Be strong,  be  honorable, be Japanese.  Stand tall. This is your birthright.
